DECISION: Run Camera Transition — Visual and Mechanical Structure

Every run opens in a low-to-the-ground third-person perspective. Players must select a minimum starting loadout before the run begins: one movement power and one offensive power. The movement power selection triggers the camera transition — a swing up and back into a DRGS-style isometric offset angle — which serves as the ritual start of every run. Each movement power has a distinct transition animation: Flight lifts the camera smoothly upward; Super Speed snaps with a motion blur; Teleportation uses a hard cut; Leaping arcs up and settles. The city layer operates on a separate camera (top-down or angled). Third-person assets are scoped to the brief intro sequence only; the isometric offset angle handles all run gameplay.

DATE: May 3, 2026

WHY: The camera transition resolves the "how does this play" question while simultaneously creating a ritual moment of hero identity at the start of every run. Movement power selection becomes expressive rather than purely mechanical — the world responds to it visually. Scoping third-person assets to the intro sequence only preserves the cinematic payoff without the maintenance cost of full third-person gameplay. The isometric offset angle maintains comic-book kinetic feel while keeping build complexity manageable.

REPLACES: Nothing — new decision

STATUS: DRAFT

